		<item>
		<title>
		Comment on Big Data to Save Gamification? by Roman Rackwitz		</title>
		<link>http://gamifyforthewin.com/2013/01/18/big-data-to-save-gamification/#comment-83</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Roman Rackwitz]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 22 Apr 2013 11:22:42 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://gamifyforthewin.com/?p=820#comment-83</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Great article. But it is also the other way round. Too often Big Data is just one thing: BIG.

And this often makes it too uncomfortable to work with it. While Gamification need big data to be able to achieve a successful context with its users it is also big data that needs the help of Gamification to make it more intuitive and understandable. 

A short story that addresses this issue :-): http://youtu.be/2bz3iLAHVks (Turn on captions)]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Great article. But it is also the other way round. Too often Big Data is just one thing: BIG.</p>
<p>And this often makes it too uncomfortable to work with it. While Gamification need big data to be able to achieve a successful context with its users it is also big data that needs the help of Gamification to make it more intuitive and understandable. </p>
<p>A short story that addresses this issue :-): <a href="http://youtu.be/2bz3iLAHVks" rel="nofollow ugc">http://youtu.be/2bz3iLAHVks</a> (Turn on captions)</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>
		Comment on Big Data to Save Gamification? by Jeff Siegel		</title>
		<link>http://gamifyforthewin.com/2013/01/18/big-data-to-save-gamification/#comment-82</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Jeff Siegel]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 02 Apr 2013 03:54:29 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://gamifyforthewin.com/?p=820#comment-82</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[This sounds similar or related to the approach I outline on my site: www.predictivegamification.com. There definitely seems to be the potential for great power in the combination of gamification, big data and predictive analytics.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>This sounds similar or related to the approach I outline on my site: <a href="http://www.predictivegamification.com" rel="nofollow ugc">http://www.predictivegamification.com</a>. There definitely seems to be the potential for great power in the combination of gamification, big data and predictive analytics.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>
		Comment on Big Data to Save Gamification? by Nadeem Akhtar		</title>
		<link>http://gamifyforthewin.com/2013/01/18/big-data-to-save-gamification/#comment-81</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Nadeem Akhtar]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 14 Mar 2013 20:06:53 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://gamifyforthewin.com/?p=820#comment-81</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Great article, the best part is the impact that Big Data can have on design of Gamified systems. Where big data is just a design tool which makes sense out of humongous data, the greater challenge lies in how the insights are used to make problems more engaging and most importantly FUN to do.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Great article, the best part is the impact that Big Data can have on design of Gamified systems. Where big data is just a design tool which makes sense out of humongous data, the greater challenge lies in how the insights are used to make problems more engaging and most importantly FUN to do.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>
		Comment on Big News: The Book is Out! by Shekar		</title>
		<link>http://gamifyforthewin.com/2012/10/31/big-news-the-book-is-out/#comment-70</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Shekar]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 07 Mar 2013 16:56:42 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://gamifyforthewin.com/?p=789#comment-70</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Dear Steve,

I am one of the students enrolled for your April 1 session on Coursera.

I was always on the lookout for a book that could help bring in the excitement of the world of entertainment and sports into the workplace. Upon your invitation, I promptly ordered the e book and your book responded to my prayers very well. 

I just now finished reading the 116 pages in one go (3 hours) and it was simply unputdownable.

I am looking forward to the course with great expectations and enthusiasm.

Ideally I would like to market my forthcoming book in an interactive way adopting the 6 step process outlined in Pages 66-74. I hope to work on this project alongside the six week session.

Thank you very much.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Dear Steve,</p>
<p>I am one of the students enrolled for your April 1 session on Coursera.</p>
<p>I was always on the lookout for a book that could help bring in the excitement of the world of entertainment and sports into the workplace. Upon your invitation, I promptly ordered the e book and your book responded to my prayers very well. </p>
<p>I just now finished reading the 116 pages in one go (3 hours) and it was simply unputdownable.</p>
<p>I am looking forward to the course with great expectations and enthusiasm.</p>
<p>Ideally I would like to market my forthcoming book in an interactive way adopting the 6 step process outlined in Pages 66-74. I hope to work on this project alongside the six week session.</p>
<p>Thank you very much.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
			</item>
